  "solution": {
    "approach": "The problem only requires converting hours to minutes and seconds. For each test case we read the integer hour, multiply it by 60 to obtain minutes and by 3600 to obtain seconds. Both operations are O(1). Using 64‑bit integers avoids overflow because the maximum value is 1000 × 3600 = 3,600,000 which fits easily in a long. The algorithm processes each test case independently, so the total time is linear in the number of test cases.",
    "timeComplexity": "O(T) where T is the number of test cases (each test case is processed in constant time).",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(1) extra space besides the input and output buffers.",
    "code": {
      "C": "",
      "C++": "",
      "Java": "import java.io.*;import java.util.*;public class Main{public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException{BufferedReader br=new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));String line=br.readLine();if(line==null||line.isEmpty())return;int T=Integer.parseInt(line.trim());StringBuilder sb=new StringBuilder();for(int i=0;i<T;i++){String s=br.readLine();while(s!=null&&s.trim().isEmpty()){s=br.readLine();}long hour=Long.parseLong(s.trim());long minutes=hour*60L;long seconds=hour*3600L;sb.append(minutes).append('\\n').append(seconds);if(i!=T-1)sb.append('\\n');}System.out.print(sb.toString());}}",
      "Python3": "",
      "JavaScript": ""
    }
